<HEAD>Bonnie Guiton Selected for Office of Consumer Affairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 3 grafs new with Consumer Affairs appointment; picks up
4th graf pvs, Davila an administrator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday named Bonnie Guiton,
an assistant secretary of education for vocational and adult
education, as director of the Office of Consumer Affairs in the
Department of Health and Human Services.
   A former vice president of Kaiser Center Inc. and vice chairman
of the U.S. Postal Rate Commission, she will succeed Virginia
Knauer in the HHS post.
   Bush also announced his selection of Robert Davila and Nell
Carney for top posts in the Education Department.
   Davila, an administrator at Gallaudet University for the
hearing-impaired, was named assistant secretary of the Office of
Special Education and Rehabilitative Services. Mrs. Carney,
assistant director for Virginia's department for the visually
handicapped, will be commissioner of the Rehabilitation Services
Administration.
   Davila is currently vice president for pre-college programs at
Gallaudet and a professor of education. A graduate of Gallaudet, he
previously served in other education posts.
   Mrs. Carney also has a background in education, as a teacher in
the Washington public school system from 1984 to 1985, an
administator in the Washington State Department for the Blind, and
counselor and instructor in Nashville public schools.
   In other appointments, the Education Department announced that
Michael Vader will be deputy assistant secretary in the Office of
Special Education and Rehabilitative Services, and Judy Schrag will
be director of the Office of Special Education Services.
</TEXT>
